ically. My mom didn’t though and it was a very good thing. I was intellectually very advanced and quicky became board of kindergarten and displayed a wide array of social problems because of it. They decided to switch me to a french school to challange me and it was exactly what I needed. To be pushed forward, not backwards. &#10;Now with my daughter, I see her around children her age and she is the smallest. Most people mistake her for a 3yr old. I hated being smaller than everybody else, but I can’t hold her back because of it. Like your son, she writes her full name and can add and subtract already. If I held her back it would be for me not her. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="960" language="en" documentId="5383" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Christina in Canada" date="March 7, 2013 at 9:22 am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://blogs.babycenter.com/mom_stories/03072013-the-big-kindergarten-question-to-redshirt-or-not/" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5383" notes="" title="The big kindergarten question: To redshirt or not?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="634"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="635" end="960"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>